03988nam a22005535i 9780300178500DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20122012ctu    fo  d z      eng d  a97803001785007 a10.12987/97803001785002doi  a(DE-B1597)486110  a(OCoLC)994604159  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  actucUS-CT 4aHQ767.9b.Y667 2012 7aSOC0470002bisacsh04a305.232231 aYoung-Bruehl, Elisabeth, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aChildism /cElisabeth Young-Bruehl. 1aNew Haven, CT : bYale University Press, c[2012] 4c©2012  a1 online resource (320 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction: What’s In A Word? -- tChapter 1. Anatomy Of A Prejudice -- tChapter 2. Three Forms Of Childism: Anna’s Story -- tChapter 3. Child Abuse And Neglect: A Study In Confusion -- tChapter 4. The Politicization Of Child Abuse -- tChapter 5. Mass Hysteria And Child Sexual Abuse -- tChapter 6. Forms Of Childism In Families -- tChapter 7. Education And The End Of Childism -- tBibliographic Essay -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn this groundbreaking volume on the human rights of children, acclaimed analyst, political theorist, and biographer Elisabeth Young-Bruehl argues that prejudice exists against children as a group and that it is comparable to racism, sexism, and homophobia. This prejudice-“childism”-legitimates and rationalizes a broad continuum of acts that are not “in the best interests of children,” including the often violent extreme of child abuse and neglect. According to Young-Bruehl, reform is possible only if we acknowledge this prejudice in its basic forms and address the motives and cultural forces that drive it, rather than dwell on the various categories of abuse and punishment.“There will always be individuals and societies that turn on their children," writes Young-Bruehl, “breaking the natural order Aristotle described two and a half millennia ago in his Nichomachean Ethics." In Childism, Young-Bruehl focuses especially on the ways in which Americans have departed from the child-supportive trends of the Great Society and of the United Nations Convention on the Rights of the Child.Many years in the making, Childism draws upon a wide range of sources, from the literary and philosophical to the legal and psychoanalytic. Woven into this extraordinary volume are case studies that illuminate the profound importance of listening to the victims who have so much to tell us about the visible and invisible ways in which childism is expressed.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aAge discrimination. 0aChildren. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Children's Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831105379940 cprintz978030017311640uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/978030017850040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300178500423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300178500/original  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY